But some researchers questioned the reliability of the data and pointed to the connection of some experts with the tobacco industry.
In an editorial in the medical journal Lancet last month criticized the "extremely shaky argument," on the basis of which PHE built its main conclusion.
In the BMJ article, two more researchers wondered whether these statements had "a firm or infidel basis."
Martin McKee, a professor in European health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, a professor of clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: "The fundamental principle of health care - the rules should be based on evidence of effectiveness."
