"Sonogenetics" allows you to control the brain's cells with sound waves
The video shows nematodes changing direction when they are exposed to sound impulses.
Scientists have brought out worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled using the pulses of sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction of movement at the moment when they are affected by sound impulses, too high for the human ear to hear them.
The pulses are affected by activating neurons genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves.
Researchers control brain activity with light
Scientists said that the worms demonstrate the capabilities of a new technique called "sonogenetics," the essence of which is the use of ultrasound to excite certain cells of the brain, heart and muscles, while the source of ultrasound is located outside the body.
Srikant Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute, La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are sent to the human brain and used in the treatment of Parkinson's disease.
The worms do not usually respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they began to react when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify ultrasonic waves, which then penetrate the worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves affect structures called "ionic TRP-4 channels" found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Ultrasound waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are associated with them, according to a report in Nature Communications.
To create nematodes that can be controlled by ultrasound, Chalasani made genetic modifications of worms, so that their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
During the use of ultrasound for the effects on modified organisms, sound waves were amplified by microscopic bubbles and introduced into the worms" organisms, activating modified motor neurons.
This technique is similar to the one used in "optogenetics" - a new direction that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons with light pulses.
Chalasani argues that, compared to this technique, sonogenetics may have some advantages.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the desired section of the brain by fiber, low-frequency ultrasonic waves pass freely through the tissues of the body, so you do not need to go inside the skull.
"We believe that for the treatment of some neurological diseases in clinical conditions, the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses will be able to make human neurons sensitive to an ultrasound signal for a while," Chalasani said.
He added that, in addition, the technique can be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
