Kiev ripped off nuclear weapons.
Kiev has officially formalized the refusal of Ukraine from cooperation with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnytsky NPP.
The Verkhovna Rada on Wednesday, on the second attempt, still voted to terminate the agreement with Moscow.
Agreements on the completion of the third and fourth blocks were signed in 2010-2012, but it was not possible to start the project.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted a law ending the agreement concluded in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth block at the Khmelnytsky NPP.
The bill was carried out by the government only from the second vote, for the first time it was supported by 210 deputies with the required minimum of 226, but then 234 members of parliament voted for the project.
The Khmelnitsky NPP laid down under the USSR under the original project was to consist of four power units of 1 GW with VVER reactors, but managed to build only two.
Negotiations with Moscow on completion led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement in 2010, in 2011-2012 the Rada adopted relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that the blocs will have to be built on a loan from the Russian side, but the funds were not allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the subsequent cooling in relations between the two countries, Kiev began to curtail relations with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing the refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnytsky nuclear power plant and the project to build a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only area where relations have been preserved remained purchases of fuel for the existing Ukrainian nuclear power plants in the Russian Federation (provided about half of the generation of electricity in the country), since so far the Ukrainian NNEGC "Energoatom" has nothing to replace Russian supplies.
Plans for the completion of the Khmelnitsky NPP with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet been finally abandoned: in 2014, Kiev announced negotiations with the Czech Skoda JS.
