FedEx revenue is mixed, the decline in forecasts for 2016.
FedEx reported on the disappointing results of the last quarter, and the delivery service giant reduced the forecast of annual profit due to falling demand for freight services and rising costs in its land transportation division.
The company also said it plans to hire approximately 55,000 seasonal workers on the holidays.
At the same time, FedEx reported last year that it would hire 50,000 temporary workers on the holidays.
Its shares fell by about 2.5 percent at preliminary trading 45 minutes before the opening of the exchange on Wednesday.
FedEx Corp. said it plans to earn between $10.40 and $10.90 in the fiscal year, which ends next May, 20 cents less than the previous forecast.
Analysts assumed $10.84 according to a FactSet review.
The decline in the forecast is observed despite the increase in rates by an average of 4.9 percent, which will come into force on January 4, and an increase in fees for ground transportation of heavy or dimensional cargo, which begins in November.
The company said it still plans to grow revenue from last year thanks to lower spending, higher gross revenue and growth in online trading.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith said the company "worked stably, taking into account the weak, compared to the forecast, economic conditions, especially in production and world trade."
Workforce plans on holidays were announced the day after a competitor's announcement, UPS, that they were planning to hire an additional 95,000 employees, about the same as they hired last year.
For the quarter that ended on August 31, FedEx earned $692 million, 6 percent more than a year earlier.
Revenue per share was $2.42, close to the forecast of an average of $2.44 per share conducted by Zacks Investment Research by a survey of 12 analysts.
Revenue increased by 5 percent, to 12.3 billion. The dollars.
Six analysts surveyed by Zacks estimated $12.23 billion. The dollars.
FedEx has suffered in recent years from a downturn in the urgent international transport sector, which has led to a lack of growth in gross revenue in its express transport unit.
However, the Internet shopping boom has dramatically improved the results in FedEx Ground.
In the last quarter, revenue from ground transportation increased by 29 percent, but operating income remained generally unchanged due to increased costs for large shipments and self-insurance.
The express transport unit received a higher income due to higher base rates, while in the cargo sector, income fell due to higher labor costs.
At preliminary trading about an hour before the opening of the exchange, FedEx shares fell by $3.85 or 2.5 percent - to $150.15.
They closed Tuesday, falling 11 percent for the year and 17 percent below the record of June 11.
At the most anticipated meeting in a few years of meeting, the heads of the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week at the 27-foot table of Honduran mahogany, deciding whether it is time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in almost ten years.
At one end of the richly decorated meeting room two-floors high over them will hang a wall image of the United States.
This map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the country's economic interests above all the others.
The Central Bank received a double order from Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and keep stable prices here.
But since the Great Recession, the leaders of the Federal system have recognized that there is a third, unwritten order: financial stability.
And this third assignment could prove to be an unknown factor in the nearly predicted decision that will be announced on Thursday, whether the U.S. economy is ready to break away from the unprecedented stimulus provided by the nearly zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Even though most data show strong economic growth, recent turmoil in global financial markets can deter already cautious leaders of the Federal system from adding volatility by raising the base rate on federal funds - even a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important subject of consideration," said Lindsay M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I think that if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty around the world market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Federal Reserve will do, which in itself provokes fluctuations in the financial market.
About half of the economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg predicted an increase in interest rates this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the federal system to hold back, with the key indicator showing only about 30 percent of the probability of a quick rise.
This can lead to a fall in the stock market if the Federal System raises the rate, provided that those who make decisions do not soften the blow of the promise that the next increase will not be soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones index rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The take-off was prompted by expectations that the individuals that determine the strategy of the Federal system will leave a bet this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research.
"It will be a surprise if the federal system raises rates at this point in time," he said.
If the leadership of the Federal Reserve does that, "they will have to go far in approving their strategy to keep the financial markets in their hands so that they don't panic."
Other experts objected that a rate hike could reassure financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the federal system would operate.
Just a month ago, the Federal System seems to have leaned in levies to a rate of 0.25 percent this month, making the first small step in slow tightening of financial conditions, which could confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that it expects a rate hike this year, despite complaints from liberals that greater economic progress is needed.
Although the emergence of new jobs slowed in August, labor market growth has been stable this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years, and almost at a level that the federal system is considered full-time.
Rising wages show signs of acceleration.
And, although inflation continues to be below the central bank's annual average of 2%, the leadership of the Federal system said that the key reason was the temporary effect of a sharp fall in oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates, and it needs them, taking into account the reduction of the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to shake late last month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones average index for industrial stock fell as much as 16% relative to a record high in May, as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy could hamper global growth.
The market has partially regained its position this month, and the Dow Jones index is now about 10% lower than the high May value.
For the leadership of the Federal Reserve, market indignation further complicates the difficult calculations of the interest rate increase.
"In the absence of information about what happened in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the past few weeks, they would have started to tighten the nuts at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate, and former Federal Reserve officer.
Now, he predicts, they will be waiting for at least a month to gain more control over the consequences.
"There is great uncertainty about the consequences for the U.S. economy, and they have almost no reliable data since China's recent events," Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not the main concern of the Federal system, and it should not be taken into account in making these decisions.
But in essence, the Federal Reserve has become global financial power.
The influence of the Central Bank in recent years has been enormous.
A hint from then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013. that the Federal Reserve could "muffle" its monetary expansion has sparked market turmoil around the world.
In a world where markets and economic systems are increasingly intertwined, it would be expected that the heads of the Federal Reserve will not only monitor developments everywhere, but also consult with representatives of other central banks and with experts to better understand the world economy.
Their decision-making process is "rather art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of Envestnet Inc, a company that deals with global state management strategies.
Jeffrey Laker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, said this month that "the history of the Federal Reserve has had cases of overreaction to the movements of the financial market that do not seem to be related to economic principles."
Lacker, a member with the voting rights of the influential Federal Open Market Committee, who insisted on a rate hike, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
