Diabetics with low obesity can help with obesity surgery
The beneficial effect of obesity in people with low obesity who suffer from type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to say that diabetics with little obesity live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
"The death rate is not immediately apparent," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert on obesity surgery, who wrote about a new study in the editor's column, JAMA Surgery.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses various methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the ability of organizations to digest food.
In a few years, bariatric surgery has proven effective for treating type 2 diabetes, but major studies have been conducted among people with morphid obesity who have a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, weight measure relative to height, is considered normal at a value of 18.5 to 24.9.
The BMI of 25 or higher suggests that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI above 30 are considered obese people.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from Taiwan's Min-Sheng Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery - stomach abyss and sleeve gastroectomies, with type 2 diabetes treatment in people with low obesity.
The average BMI in those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of their participation in the study.
At the same time, the BMI of those who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes remains at about 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% were completely cured of diabetes, and partially 28%.
In the group that received drug treatment, for comparison, the complete cure for diabetes was observed only in 1%, and partial - only about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol "was generally better in the surgical group," the authors say.
The researchers also controlled blood hemoglobin levels in the blood that reflect blood sugar levels in dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c is better to keep below 7%, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the therapeutic group, however, it remained stable at about 8%.
But the best glycemic control rates reflected by good A1c hemoglobin levels have not reduced the death rate in five years, according to research manager Dr. Chi-Ceng Soo and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results of two types of surgical treatment.
On the fifth year, compared to the group that had heated a sleeve gastrectomy, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs. 14.2 kg), achieved a greater reduction in the BMI (by 7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%), and was also closer to complete diabetes remission (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although a new study does not demonstrate the benefits of a surgical method in terms of life expectancy after five years, there is evidence from a study of people with overweight in Sweden that surgical treatment does lead to an increase in life expectancy, according to Blackstone of the College of Medicine in the city. Phoenix, University of Arizona.
According to a Swedish study for obese people who chose bariatric interference, the likelihood of dying for 15 years was about 29% lower than the group that used more traditional methods.
Although the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that this encourages people with a BMI below 35 interested in such a procedure.
"The report is very important here, as it claims that such surgery is safe in a group with low BMI where there is an increased risk of death or renal disease," she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should begin to take weight seriously once the patient's BMI falls between 27 to 30.
"I think we've been waiting too long to get people to take this seriously," she said.
It seems to me that once they accumulate genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is very difficult to reverse.
