The Nobel laureate: globalization
The processes of globalization should have helped to reduce inequalities in the world.
In fact, the situation looks different, the difference in income of the population in developing economies, on the contrary, is growing.
Eric Maskin.
To correct this, it is necessary to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers, said the chief researcher of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Choice of Decisions of the Higher School of Economics, Nobel Prize laureate in economics 2007. Eric Maskin.
In the last 20 years, the world has experienced unprecedented growth in global markets.
Trade borders between countries have become increasingly open.
Proponents of globalization predicted great benefits for emerging economies.
"And these forecasts have come true in many ways," Maskin emphasizes.
For example, China and India have received serious GDP growth per capita.
However, not everything is so rosy.
It was expected that globalization would shorten the gap between the "hustle" and the "undesup" in poor countries, which manifests itself in a large income inequality, or rather, wages.
But in fact, this inequality has only increased, notes Eric Maskin in his article "Why global markets haven't reduced inequality in emerging economies," published in The World Bank Economic Review, which was translated and quoted by HSE.
Together with an economist, Harvard University professor Michael Kremer, Eric Maskin, has developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why income differences in poor countries increase as globalization grows, recalls I.E.
There are specific processes in the new global market.
To demonstrate them, Maskin highlights four levels of qualification - A and B for rich countries, C and D for the poor.
After globalization, D specialists from poor countries do not have enough qualifications to cooperate with specialists A and B from rich countries.
And if the C-level workers from poor countries" salaries are growing due to cooperation with B employees from the rich, then D workers do not feel growth or their salaries are falling at all.
The resulting effect is that the internationalization of production will increase the pay gap between the two categories of professionals in poor countries and consequently increase inequality.
Kremer and E. Maskins are proposed an amazingly beautiful model, an alternative to the Ricardian theory of comparative advantages.
It explains why globalization has led to income inequality, says Fuad Aleskerov, an ordinary professor, head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision Selection, Head of the Department of Mathematics at HSE.
And like every powerful theory, I'm sure it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this field.
The solution to the problem, according to Eric Maskin, is to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as the scientist notes, do not have funds for this, and it is unprofitable for companies to pay for their training.
In such a situation, governments, international agencies, NGOs and private funds can play a significant role, Muskin believes.
The scientist notes that the developed theory in no case calls for the halt to the process of globalization, which has brought and bears fruit in the form of GDP growth.
Derbent: a live connection of times.
Derbent - one of the most ancient cities in Russia - celebrates its 2000th anniversary in September.
The program of festive events includes the festival of national cultures of the peoples of Dagestan and the fair in the style of past times, the exhibition of derbent carpets and the Day of Open Churches, the historical and musical show "2000 years in two hours" and excursions to the reconstructed Peter I Museum.
Medieval stones of the fortress of Naryn-Kala, ancient Arabic inscriptions on the walls, narrow streets and palace gardens - all this seemed to come off the pages of "Thousands and One Nights."
Derbent is the only city in Russia that has been preserved in its place since ancient times.
Although it was claimed by the Roman Empire, Byzantium, the Khazar Khaganate and the Golden Horde.
The age of the Eastern plane trees, which grow in the courtyard of the Derbent Juma Mosque, is equal to several centuries.
These powerful plants are under the protection of the All-Russian program "Trees - monuments of wildlife."
The shadow of scattered crowns saves pilgrims and tourists during the summer heat.
The visitor of the mosque will pour fragrant tea and be fomented with Dagestani treats - honey figs, hurrime, mushrooms, fungal, fungal, airan and sweets.
In Derbent for centuries, they use large samovars to drink the tea of many guests.
The inscription above the entrance to Juma Mosque says that the building was built in the year 115 AH.
That is, in 733 on the Gregorian calendar.
This is the oldest mosque in Russia.
The interior is striking in scope and solemnity: the arcades of domes and vaults are based on square columns and are illuminated by the rays of the sun from tiny windows.
The content and breeding of pigeons is a traditional hobby of the residents of Derbent.
Bird owners put dove daggers in the yards, under trees, in the attic.
An exciting spectacle - taking up flocks of white pigeons into the sky, similar to the flashes of festive fireworks.
In defense against the enemy, the ancient Persians blocked the Caspian Gate with a double stone wall.
Going 500 meters into the sea, this structure was locked by the harbor of Derbent.
In 2003, the fortress walls of Derbent were included in the UNESCO World Heritage List as the best-preserved monument of ancient Persian fortification architecture.
Carpets in Derbent were weaved in the 5th century, and until now the technology of this unique craft has been preserved almost unchanged.
On one of the streets adjacent to the city market, carpets are sold for every taste - palasses of wool, cotton or felt of all colors and shades, with a pile and without it, with a complex ornament and a bizarre border.
The development of the city began with the Magalov - quarters with one-storey stone buildings.
