Kumar is the head of the National Green Tribunal (NZT), a judicial authority established in 2010 to halt rapid environmental pollution that has accompanied the rapid economic growth of recent decades.
During this time, the Tribunal has heard more than 10,000 lawsuits related to air pollution, garbage collection, geological developments, toxic waste and dams.
In two of the three cases, the court decides to terminate the construction leading to pollution.
The stakes are incredibly high: in 60 years since the independence of the enhanced industrial development, India has evolved from a country of virgin jungle to one of the most overcrowded and polluted countries in the world.
The problem is especially acute in large megacities, where the development of infrastructure does not keep up with the rapid urbanization: cities are covered with dense smog, the rivers are filled with pesticides and waste from enterprises and households, and the remaining residential areas are cut down for new residential areas.
Despite the formal support of the green movement by the state, the NZT is regularly criticized by the government of Narendra Modi, as it often becomes the main reason for the cancellation of the largest investment projects.
So, in May of this year, the Minister of the Environment called the court's decisions "extreme" and "unfull."
