Xi calls for making economy more open to the world
The economy must become more open to the world to spur its growth, as President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday in an address to the group facing the challenge of leading the reforms.
"China should focus on attracting foreign investors and experts and develop a policy of openness," he said, addressing the 16th meeting of the Committee of the Central Leading Group on Comprehensive Reforms.
According to him, the expansion of openness and deepening reforms will give the economy a new impetus and vitality and provide a new space for economic development.
The lead group adopted a number of directives, including the introduction of investor access to the market, changing the rules of border control, the promotion of state-owned enterprises (SOEs) attracting private capital and revising the system of registration of residents.
According to the statement, a list of sectors of the economy and production that are not available for investment will be compiled.
The system will be gradually depleted through trial programs.
This is an important step, as it will give the market a more significant role in the allocation of resources, ensuring the rule of law in the business sphere and increasing openness, as stated in the statement.
The government will also ease control of the powers conferred on companies, ensuring that companies operate their own businesses.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to develop new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to strengthen local growth.
Even more areas will be available to private investors in order to increase the openness of state-controlled sectors of the economy.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investors and will protect the legitimate interests of companies with foreign financing, as well as provide them with better conditions," the statement said.
In addition, the procedure for applying for a permanent residence permit for foreigners, or "grin-card," will be facilitated by optimizing the requirements and simplifying the filing process itself.
The meeting also discussed the provision of the rights of lawyers and the training of professional judges and prosecutors.
According to the official report issued after the meeting, it was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and ministers Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli.
